WEBVTT

1
00:00:03.600 --> 00:00:16.296
Here's the part of the Doomsday Budget that quietly saves
accounts. The rotation ladder. It answers a question every
funded trader eventually runs into. What do you do when
one account simply isn't enough to survive the bad streak?

2
00:00:16.896 --> 00:00:30.240
Remember the doomsday drawdown. The deepest hole your
worst losing streak can dig. If that hole is bigger than a
single account's limit, one account busts. And the fix
isn't trading smaller. It's spreading that same streak
across more accounts.

3
00:00:30.840 --> 00:00:42.000
This little table is the whole idea. Read it row by row.
Each row is a number of prop accounts, the total bank you
need standing behind them, and the longest losing streak
that setup can actually survive.

4
00:00:42.600 --> 00:00:58.824
With one account, you need about thirty-nine hundred
dollars in bank, and you survive a three-in-a-row streak.
Add a second account and that climbs to roughly seventy-
seven hundred, but now you survive six in a row. Three
accounts, eleven and a half thousand, and you can ride out
nine straight losers.

5
00:00:59.424 --> 00:01:14.640
See the pattern? Every account you add doesn't just add
money. It buys you a longer survivable streak. Because the
losses get shared across the rotation, instead of all
piling onto one balance. That is exactly how trading desks
ride out runs that would wipe a solo trader.

6
00:01:15.240 --> 00:01:32.568
The footnote hands you the working rule. Keep about twice
the per-account doomsday as bank for every prop. Add a
prop above that line and you can size up. Drop below it
and you're one bad streak from zero. And it ends with the
real secret. Diversify across uncorrelated moves, so they
don't all lose on the same day.

7
00:01:33.168 --> 00:01:40.248
One account is a bet. A funded rotation is a business.
This ladder tells you exactly how big that business needs
to be.
